abstract: Mr. HUNTER called up the Army Appropriator bill. Mr. SLIDELL asked leave to make an explanation He announced that he would make no further attempt to bring up the bill for the acquisition fo Cuba. He said, at an early hour yesterday Mr. WADE, of Ohio having announced his intention to speak against the bill, took the floor and mored to adjourn.

abstract: The most startling incident in the news of the morning is the dreadful homicide of PHILIP BARTON KEY by the lion. DANIEL E. SICKLES, of this City. The details of this sad affair will be found in our special dispatches from Washington. They give all the facts essential to the case. Mr. KEY had inflicted upon Mr. SICKLES the greatest injury and the most intolerable dishonor possible.

abstract: ENFORCING THE POLICE LAWS. -- It is reported that the Police Commissioners have at length determined to enforce the rules adopted for the government of the Police Department. It is said that smoking while on duty, being off heat at roll call, or visiting saloons to obtain refreshments will, if reported, be followed either by a fine or dismissal from the service.

abstract: By the arrival of the South American mails, by the Avon, at Southampton, we have dates from Rio to Jan. 8. Vast quantities of rain had fallen at Rio, and the streets were inundated. A portion of the railway had been damaged by the rains. It was feared that yellow fever would shortly make its appearance at Rio from the want of sanitary measures.

abstract: Business continues rather depressed, at al although in anything there hail been improvement until the occurrences of the last few days. News has been received here of an outbreak in Copiape. This took place amount the 5th inst. among the city police, who are a military body ; the extent of this movement is at present uncertain. The steam frigate Esmeralda has been dispatched with troops to quell the revolt.

abstract: The Panama Railroad Company's Mail steamship Columbus. Capt. LUDWIG, arrived in this harbor from Central American ports on the morning of the 6th. She left San Jose de Guatemala on the 27th of January, La Union, Salvador, on the 30th, Realejo, Nicaragua, on the 1st of February, and Panta Arenas de Costa Rica on the 31.

abstract: To the Editor of the New-York Times; When all execution against the property his been returned unsatisfied, the law of our State allows an examination of the judgment debtor. under oath, to discover what property he has.
